definition.value: An organic monosodium salt of gold thiomalic acid, comprising a sodium cation and a monovalent aurothiomalate anion.
An organic sodium salt which is the disodium salt of gold thiomalic acid, with a basic unit comprising two sodium cations and a divalent aurothiomalate anion.
Any monocarboxylic acid which also contains a separate (alcoholic or phenolic) hydroxy substituent.
Any monocarboxylic acid having at least one additional oxo functional group.
Anhydrides derived from carboxylic acids.
A crown ether that is 18-crown-6 ortho-fused to two benzene rings at positions 8-9 and 17-18.
The saturated hydrides of tervalent phosphorus having the general formula PnHn+2.
The simplest of the diphosphanes, consisting of two covelently linked phosphorus atoms each carrying two hydrogens.

Phosphane (PH3) and compounds derived from it by substituting one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups: RPH2, R2PH, R3P (R =/= H) are called primary, secondary and tertiary phosphines, respectively. A specific phosphine is preferably named as a substituted phosphane.
A compound derived from phosphane by substituting one hydrogen atom by a hydrocarbyl group.
A compound derived from phosphane by substituting two hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.
A compound derived from phosphane by substituting three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.
lambda(5)-phosphane and its hydrocarbyl derivatives. By extension the term also applies to phosphonium ylides.
A Glu-Cys-Gly tripeptide derivative of glutathione containing a 2-hydroxyethyl substituent on the S of the Cys residue.
That isomer of butenoic acid having the double bond at position C-3.
The conjugate base of crotonic acid; used by some bacterial species as a carbon and energy source.
A butenoate having the double bond at the 3-position.
Any carboxylic acid anion containing at least one oxo group.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of a 4-(3-hydroxy-1-benzothiophen-2-yl)-2-oxobut-3-enoic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of glutaric acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of glutaramic acid.
Any monocarboxylic acid having a 2-oxo substituent.
A steroid ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of a sterol.
